  <scaffolding>
    <layer level="1" name="Layer 1">
      <focus/>
      <content>Basic terms and concepts: Backup (copy of data for recovery [https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/other/2020/04/24/protecting-data-from-ransomware-and-other-data-loss/final]); Data Integrity (accuracy/completeness post-event [https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/1800/11/final]); Restoration Testing (verifying usability [https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/other/2020/04/24/protecting-data-from-ransomware-and-other-data-loss/final]); Ransomware/Destructive Events.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="2" name="Layer 2">
      <focus/>
      <content>Frameworks and structure: NIST CSF PR.IP-4 (backups conducted, maintained, tested [https://www.baculasystems.com/blog/nist-requirements-backup]); Backup types (full, incremental, differential); Testing elements (integrity checks, full restore simulation, frequency scheduling); Concept map: Central 'Backup Restoration Testing' → branches 'Integrity Check', 'Full Restore Simulation', 'Frequency Scheduling'; links to NIST SP 800-184, NISTIR 8428.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="3" name="Layer 3">
      <focus/>
      <content>Practical steps: 1) Select test environment (isolated VM); 2) Verify backup integrity (checksums); 3) Perform partial/full restore; 4) Validate functionality (data accuracy, app operability); 5) Document results (success rate, time); 6) Clean up and report.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="4" name="Layer 4">
      <focus/>
      <content>Advanced connections: Position in NIST IR Lifecycle Recovery phase (post-Containment/Eradication); Big picture: Reduces downtime/costs (3x faster per NIST); Optimization (quarterly tests, automate where possible); Links to full IR (Preparation → Recovery); NISTIR 8428: 'Digital Forensics and Incident Response Reference Corpus' – provides corpus for IR tools/testing relevance [https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/nistirs/8428/ipd].</content>
    </layer>
  </scaffolding>
